ggplot(data = mpg) + geom_point(mapping = aes(x = hwy, y = cyl))

  1. The plot does not show a useful comparison because multiple of the dependent variables (drv) apply to the independent.
ggplot(data = mpg) + geom_point(mapping = aes(x = class, y = drv))

3.3 Exercises

  1. The ‘color = “blue”’ should be outside the first parentheses. Inside the parentheses, it counts the color as a variable in the function.

  2. The categorial variables are manufacturer, model, trans, drv, fl, and class. The continuous variables are displ, year, cyl, cty, and hwy. This information is visible in the data set by comparing the variables answered with categories versus numerics.

  3. When mapped to color, categorical variables appear in different colors for each category. Continuous variables appear in a hue of one color and not much information is given.

ggplot(data = mpg) + geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color = cty))

When mapped to size, continuous variables appear in the size that corresponds to the value (larger value, larger size). Categorical variables are randomly assigned to a size.

ggplot(data = mpg) + geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, size = cty))

When mapped to shape, categorical variables are each assigned to a different shape. Continuous variables will not map to shape.

  1. The same variable can be mapped to multiple aesthetics. For a continuous variable this is redundant.
ggplot(data = mpg) + geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color = cty, size = cty))

  1. The stroke aesthetic refers to the size of the stroke of a shape. It only works for shapes 21-24.
?geom_point
  1. The color changes for when the displ variable is <5.
ggplot(data = mpg) + geom_point(mapping = aes(x = cty, y = hwy, colour = displ < 5))

3.5 Exercises

  1. If you facet on a continuous variable, it creates too many facets that have little significance to the data.
ggplot(data = mpg) + geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + facet_wrap(~cty)

  1. The empty cells mean that no cars have both that kind of cylinder and wheel-drive. They relate to that plot by representing the spaces on the plot with no points.
ggplot(data = mpg) + geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + facet_grid(drv ~ cyl)

ggplot(data = mpg) + geom_point(mapping = aes(x = drv, y = cyl))

  1. The . makes the facets horizontal.
ggplot(data = mpg) + geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + facet_grid(drv ~ .)

ggplot(data = mpg) + geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + facet_grid(. ~ cyl)

  1. The advantages of using faceting instead of the color aesthetic is that its more organized and the variables are distinct and clear. The disadvantages are that they are not on the same plot. If you had a larger dataset, the faceting aesthetic would become busier and less clear.

  2. nrow is the number of rows and ncol is the number of columns. facet_grid does not have these controls because the number of rows and columns are fixed by the variables in the facet.

  3. This variable should go in the columns because there are more facets and it would be harder to read in rows.
